{"/service/ndnp/sdhi/batch_sdhi_lightning_ver01/data/sn99062049/00415624979/1910091601/0106.xml":{"full_text":"I fi\nI\nII\n5\nI\n|i\n\u2022I:-!\nI\n^aX\nFREI8HT RATES\nARETOO LOW\nPennsylvania Official Before\nCommerce Commission.\nSAYS ACTION WAS DELAYED\nTariffs SI on\nI\nc{ Have Been Increased\nin 19.1J, hie Asserts, but Adjustment\nWas Put Off Because of Business\nDepression\u2014Matter Now Imperative\nBecause of Recent Advances in\nWages.\nNew York, S\"|it. in.\n-John P..\n'J'lmyi r. third vice jireKiileiil. of lie\nI'cnii niilro.nl, tolil tin: inter\nslitli' oniiueree commission, v. liii'h is\ninijiiiiiiiK into the 11njs(ion of in\ncreased Irei^ht tariffs by the lOastoru\nroads, lliat tlie rales between (lie Must\nand West lmve for yours been too low\nand that the tarlfl'.s .should have been\nraised in 190S. The adjustment, bow\never. was delayed until the business\ndepression had passed, the wilness\nsaiil.\n\"The matter of advancing rates\ncame to a bead wit I he recent wage\ndemands,\" .said Mr. Thayer. \"It is\nnot an extraordinary and unprecedent\ned advance in rales, but is in line with\nour established practice for two\nyears.\"\nMr. Thayer said that passenger\nrates were not compensatory for the\nservice rendered, but that, the public,\nthrough its legislatures, would not.\nstand for an advance in their passen\nger fares, lie said that the rates on\nthrough traffic had been too low ill\ncomparison with local rales.\nConsidering the mailer of freight\ntariffs Mr. Thayer said:\nQuestion of Freight Tariffs.\n\"A\ncar of first class freight from\nNew York or Hostoic 1.100 miles to\nChicago, would, at high speed, bring\nJust $75. A car of .steel from Pitts\nburg to New York, less than half the\ndistance, loaded and unloaded for us,\nbrings twice the revenue.\n\"On everything from lioslon to Chi\ncago we only get 55 cents a hundred\nand have to pay the New Haven rail\nroad 2(1 per cent of it for bringing it\nto -Jersey City.\"\nMr. Thayer said in conclusion:\n\"Willie the estimated Increase of\nthis advance on lines east of Pittsburg\nis $3,000,000. which is a large sum, it\nmust *be remembered as far as the\nPennsylvania railroad is concerned\ntttaat we deal with very large and huge\nfigures and, after all, that the amount\nonly represents 2.3 per cent of our\ngross earnings from freight traffic and\n1.6 per cent of our total gross earn\nings from all sources, so that it is not\nlarge standard advance, in our opin\nion, but a mere readjustment of rates\nto bring us a portion of the revenues\nwe must have in order to-meet de\nmands made upon us.\"\nTO RESUME RATE HEARINGS\nCommerce Commission Will Take Up\nCases in the West.\nWashington, Sept. 13.\u2014Judge Mar\n'tin A. Knapp, chairman of the inter\nstate commerce commission, just re\nturned from his vacation trip, gave\nassurance that the supplemental tes\ntimony in the freight rate cases, of\nboth the East and West, would bo\nheard by members of the commission.\nIt is likely that Commissioner Prouty\nwill sit in the Western case at Chi\ncago on the resumption of the hearing\non the 19th inst. If iiis health shall\n\u2022permit Commissioner Clark also may\n.be on the bench with Mr. Prouty.\nREASON FOR ACT UNKNOWN\n.Wome of Mine Official at Calumet,\nMich., Dynamited.\nCalumet, Mich., Sept. 13.\u2014An unsuc\ncessful attempt was made to kill\nFrank Phillips, master mechanic of\nthe Kearsarge mine, and his family. A\nstick of dynamite was set off, partially\nwrecking the dwelling and smashing\ndishes and other contents. Two sus\npects have been arrested. The cause\nof the deed is unknown.\nSTEAMER GROUNDS NEAR S00\n.Forward Tanks Are Punctured and\nVessel Is Beached.\nSault Ste. Marie, Mich., Sept. 13.\u2014\nThe steamer Pontiac, upbound, struck\nthe middle ground at the mouth of St.\nMary's river. The forward tanks were\npunctured aud rapidly filled. The ves\nsel was beached on Gaffneys point to\navoid sinking. The crew is safe.\nCandidate Breaks His Arm.\nMilwaukee, Sept. 13.\u2014Henry F.\nCochems, former Harvard athlete and\nWisconsin football star, will have tc\nW'lZ.f'-fi make his campaign for congress with\nhis right arm in a sling. Cochems\nwas stepping off a street car when he\nclipped, breaking bis arm above the\nelbow.\nAb'ruzzi Engagement Denied.\nRome, Sept. 18.\u2014A semi-official com\nmunication Issued by an Italian\n\u201eency declares that tte reports print\ned in Italy and abroad of the ap\nproaching\nmarriage ot the Duke of the\nwd Mis* Katharine Blklnn\nare absolutely b\u00ab\u00bb^\u00abM-\nTHREE MEN UNDER ARREST\nAre Charged With Recent Incendiary\nFires at New Duluth.\nI uiiith, Sept. 13.\u2014The sixth incen\ndiary fir\u00bb in N'ew Duluth completely\ndestroyed tin- finishing room and ware\nhouse of the Thompson Furniture\ncompany and caused a loss estimated\nat $3u,000, about, half covered by in\nsurance.\nThree men, said to have been seen\nrunning away from the scene, were\narrested on suspicion of having started\nthe conflagration and were taken to\nsel and Rob Passengers.\nHarbin, Manchuria, Sept. 13.\u2014A\nband of brigands, disguised as passen\ngers, held up a Russian steamer south\nof this port and, after a fight, over\ncame the crew and robbed the passen\ngers. In attempting to defend their\nvessel the owners, two Russians, were\nkilled and many of the Chinese crew\nand Chinese passengers were wound-'\ned.\nWhen the pirates were in control of\nthe situation they bound the passen\ngers, the crew, a Russian sailor am! I\ntwo Russian women and took the val-'\nuables of the captives at their leisure I\nA boatload of hunters who happened\nto be in the vicinity gave the alarm\nand a Russian gunboat was sent in\npursuit of the outlaws.\nTO CONNECT WITH HILL LINES\nHuge Canadian Railroad Proposition\nComes to Light.\nEdmonton, Alta. Sept. 13.\u2014A huge\nrailway proposition backed by exten\nsive New York capital for the cor.\nstruction of a line of railway which\nwill traverse the entire length of Al\nberta from the international boundary\nto Peace River landing, a distance of\nmore than 700 miles, and which will\nconnect with the Hill system in Mon\ntana, was laid befdVe Premier Sifton\nby representatives of New York capi\ntalists, railway builders and coal men,\nwho have already organized a com\npany to build the line and who have\ncompleted the surveys for the first\n100 miles. Premier Sifton affixed his\nsignature to the plans for the first 100\nmiles of the road.\nYEGGMEN WRECK THE BANK\nWatchman at Henry, S. D., Is BounJ\nand Gagged by Robbers.\nWatertown, S. D.. Sept. 13.\u2014Four\nmen wrecked the State bank of Henry\nin an attempt to blow the safe. After\nbinding and gagging the night watch\nman the robbers demolished the side\nof the vault with tools stolen from a\nsection house. Five nitroglycerin\nblasts failed to open the safe. The\nmen stole a team and a buggy with\nwhich to get out. of town.\nRobbers Hold Up Rich Autoists.\nPoughkeepsie, N. Y., Sept. 13.\nMasked bandits, working with a free\ndom of manner that would have done\nJesse James and his band proud, held\nup three wealthy Poughkeepsie resi\ndents at the point of revolvers and\nstripped, them of much jewelry, $1J0\nin cash and valuable pipers! One\nfired two shots at one of the autoists\nwho resisted being searched, narrowly\nmissing him.\nKilled for Fifteen Cents.\nGalatia, 111., Sept. 13.\u2014Walter C.\nHolliday was shot and killed by\nJoseph Wiggins at a ball game be\ntween the Thompsonvilie and Galatia\nteams. Holliday was acting as gate\nkeeper and was endeavoring to collect\n15 cents, the price of admission, from\nWiggins. Wiggins fled and is being\npursued by a posse with bloodhounds.\nChicago's Oldest Lawyer Dead.\nChicago, Sept. 13.\u2014George Laban\nPaddock, lawyer and financier, seven\nty-seven years old, is dead at his\nhome here, tn number of years of\nservice Mr. Paddock was probably the\noldest lawyer in the tilty, having spent\nfifty-one Years at his orofession\nSocial\n1\npolice headquarters for examination.\nThe fire was the most disastrous yet\nreported.\nLast week the plant of the \\V. I!.\nUieckliolT box factory was burned,\nwith a loss of $20,1100, partly insured\nPreviously tile company suffered from\ntwo tires, causing a combined loss of\nabout $\".11,000, The Thompson Kurni\ntune company had a small blaze and\nthe Xew Duluth Dumber company had\na loss of $2.ooo a short, time ago. One\n1\nof these lip undoubtedly was of in-J\nrendiary origin.\nSLAYER AND ONE VICTIM DEAD{\nJealousy Cause of Triple Shooting at:\nRed field, S. D.\nRedfield, S. D., Sept. 13.\u2014\nCrazed by\njealousy II. V. Ilarveson, a drug clerk\nof this city, shot, and killed Dale\nRiser, a prominent young lady, seri\nously wounded Dr. P. IS. Clinite, a\ndentist, and then killed himself. The\nshooting occurred at the young lady's\nhome.\nDr. Clinite had been calling upon I\nher and just as he was leaving was\nmet at the door by Ilarveson, who\nshot him twice through the right lung\nand once through the arm after\n('Unite li'id fallen, lie then shot the\ngirl above the heart, killing her al\nmost instantly. Clinite and Miss Kiser I\nfell in the hallway of the house and\nIlarveson stepped out on the porch\nand shot himself through the head.\nBRIGANDS HOLD UP STEAMER\nChinese Bandits Kill Owners of Ves\u00ad\nA Mother and iugh\nter Got TherefntlieLi:\nBy MILLARD MALT BY.\n1\nHiiht UHO, I.J' An'i'.-ric: :i t'lvf\nAssociation.\nA stagecoach lumbered up a 7.i :-.air\nroad in the I'ocky mountain On tin\noutside seat behind the drivr sat a\ngentleman whose eminently ivspei table\ntraveling suit and bis clean cut fea\ntures indicated that hu was to the\nmanner horn, Mosaic him sal a young\nman in the costume of the country,\nllis skirl was tlannel bis bat was a\n.sombrero.\nOn the next seat back .sat a lady,\nthe aristocratic gentleman's wife, and\nReside her a girl of nineteen, their\ndaughter. The man 111 the sombrero\nwas telling Ihem about the mountains\nand its people and pointing out the\nmore prominent peaks, to which the\ntravelers listened with groat interest.\nThe sun was hot, the pace was slow,\nand the two combined tended to make\nthe driver drowsy. When the coach\nreadied an eminence and started down\nan incline, instead of being wide\nawake to the dangers of mountain\ntravel, be was nodding. He not only\nfailed to put 011 the brake, bur drop\nped the reins. lie was awakened by\nthe shouts of the? passengers behind\nhim, wlio saw a terrible death staring\nthem in the face The horses, un\nchecked. started down the slope and\nwere soon going at a breakneck pace.\nThe driver hastily abandoned his\npost and, putting his foot on the iron\nslop beside him, swung himself to the\nground. The young man who bad been\npointing out objects of Interest let.\nhimself down over the foot beard on to\nthe tongue, gathered up the. reins,\nijuiekly remounted to the box, put on\nthe brake and managed to reduce the\npace sufliei 1 illly to enable the coach\nto turn a curve without going over a\nprecipice. Then after a further short\ndescent he brought, the horses to a\nstandstill. The lirst sensation that\ncan.'e to him after It was ail over was\nfee,. (be arms of the aristocratic\nget nan about Ills neck.\nOne day a couple of years after this\nepisode Mrs Murphy and her daugh\nter, while bowling along Ocean avenue\nat Newport, received a terrible shock.\n\"Oh, heavens, mother, there's Bar\nton Keith! Look the other way,\nquick!\"\nMiss Murphy, pretending to see some\nthing to which she desired to call her\nmother's attention, pointed hi the op\nposite direction from the young man,\nthe carriagfe rolled by, and the women\nbegan to discuss the situation.\n\"YVhat in the world could have\nbrought hirn here?\" exclaimed the\nmother.\n\"1 would as soon have expected to\nsee a Mississippi pilot.\"\n\"Hart has been a stage driver.\"\n\"He'll tell everybody here all about\nour antecedents.\"\n\"He won't know any one to tell.\"\n\"It seems hard to cut. hiiu after that\naffair you had with him.\"\n\"There have been changes since then.\nAt that time father was building his\nlittle branch railroad he hadn't got on\nto the main line.\"\n\"Well, I don't think there's much\ndanger, considering that he can't have\nany entree here. Heaven knows what\na time we've had to even get in on\nthe outer circle. How can Bart Keith\nwith 110 money get in at. all?\"\n\"He may be prosperous he's well\nenough dressed.\"\nThai night there was a graud func\ntion at one of the \"cottages,\" and the\nnext morning Mary Murphy ran to her\nmother with a newspaper in her hand\naud her eyes wide open.\n\"Fur bied's sake, mother, listen to\nthis: 'Among those present at Mrs\nAtherton's last night was Mr. Barton\nKeith.'\n\"Von don't mean it!\"\n\"IIow- in tile name of conscience do\nyou suppose he got in I here?\"\n\"I can't imagine I know we couldn't\nget a bid.\"\n\"He must have a pull somewhere.\"\n\"Your father had a pull. but. it didn't\nwork He offered Peter Jones a tip\non the stock of our road if he'd gel\nhim an invitation to the Athertons'.\nBut Pete said they were of the old\nNew York blue blood and rich besides.\nThese people who have both blood and\nmoney are the hardest of all to move.\"\n\"Oho! Ilvre's the explanation!\" and\nshe read a social item\nvisiting Mr. and\nMr. irton Ketlli is\nMrs. Emerson Forbes\n\"OU, my goodness gracious,\" exclaim\ned the mother, \"how in the world did\nhe ever get in with them?\"\nThere was a silence between the two\nwhich Mary ended bv saying*\n\"Mother, we've gone and done it.\"\n\"So we have.\"\nWe must find a way to take a back\ntrack.\"\n\"So we must.\"\n\"But we're entirely Ignorant of the\nkey to the position.\"\n.lWkat\ndo you lllean\nby that?\"\nWe don't know what reason the\nforbes have for taking in Bart.\"\nDo you suppose they know what\nhe's been?\"\n\"Of course they do. Bart couldn't\nkeep it If he wished. That's the sin\ngular part of it. The Forbes have\nbeen prominent in New York and New\nport society for a hundred years. But\none thing 1 have noticed In these old\nfamilies they're tnore Independent\nabout whom they take up than any\nother people. I can't Imagine those I\ni'orkinses who made their money in:\nferiiiixing material having anything to\n1:0 v.ch Hart Keilh. You know how\n1 hey Miubbed us.\"\n\"Yes. indeed I do, and I'm wailing\nfor the time to come when I can get\neven wit them.\"\n\"P.ut, mother, how are we to fix it\nup with I'.avt:\"\n\"I don know, .Maine, unless you\nhave t!:e same power you used to have\nover him\nMaii.ii cast a glance in a mirror. Art\nhad do :e a great deal for her since she\nv.niied 1 11 the railroad men her mother\nfid in their days of poverty. Nothing\nthat money could buy was now denied\nher. Hut she knew Hart Keith well,\nlie bad 1 ooil [-alien. .-mil to\nlove i.er iii costly fabrics must excite\nan entirely new sensation P.esiih s, he\nwas in 1 he swim at Newport, where li:\nwould nice: the linest costumes in\nAmerica, 10 say nothing of the women\nthey incased. To make mailers worse\nshe bed cut him. S\n\".Mother.\" she said, \"1 believe I'll\nwrite him a line saying I've heard of|\nhis being in Newport and tolling him\nwe're bore. That'll look as if we\nhadn't seen him on the avenue.\"\n\"Ho you think he'd tumble to It 7\"\nThe girl pondered awhile, then ad\nmitted that she knew very well he\nwould their eyes had met and there\nhad been a mutual recognition. She\nflare not write the note.\nHut one morning she received a note\nfrom Keith. He told her that, having\nheard she was at Newport, he had\ncome 011 from the west to find her. P.ut\ntime had made great changes for both\nof them and he did not doubt she was\nfollowing a course which seemed in\nviting to her in her new sphere. lie\nshrank from parting with her without\nletting her kis.nv that lie had kept the\nboyish promises made years ago. lie\nrefrained from mentioning the cut she\nhad given him, but it was evident it\nwas this that had turned him from\nher lie closed his epistle with the\nword \"farewell.\" and she knew that\nhe had passed beyond recall.\nFor a time the Murphys heard that\nKeith was being introduced under the\nwing of the Forbes Then I hey began\nto hear his name mentioned among the\npeople and in the society notes inde\npendently of his introducers, and it\nwas not long before they learned that\nwhich travels on the wings of the\nwind Keith was rich. He had be\ncome interested In certain western\nspeculations with Mr. Forbes and the\ntwo had made money together. Then\ncame a rumor that Keith was to marry\nMiss Alice Forbes.\nUp to this time the Murphys had\nmerely wondered. Now they were\nastonished. And over Mary Murphy\ncame a wave of regret. It was not\nfor the loss of Barton Keith's wealth\nor position it was for Keith himself.\nThe prize they sought for and for\nwhich she had snubbed the lover of\nher young girlhood every day seemed\nfurther from her grasp. Despite their\nmillions, the Murphys found It im\npossible to effect an entrance into\nNewport society. Mary had become\naccustomed to wealth, and it failed to\nsatisfy her She was hungry for the\nboyish love that bad been hers In\npoverty, but she had thrown it away.\nTh fee'c-i ti.-it Keith was to marry\nMiss ,\\:i l*.:\"':es proved rt'.e When\nthe \\y:s formally an\nnoun i:r .'.iys read the so\nsic'v 1: a New Y.:k news\n.ry 1 n-- erning the contract\ning r:: that gave them the key\nto l-i. *:':i::! oii it told how Mr and\nMrs Fori and their daughter were\ntraveling in the Itoeky mountains, how\na stage driver fell asleep, how a young\nman who had been formerly a handler\nof the ribbons saved the passengers\nfrom death, how Mr. Forbes had taken\nhim up and enabled him to make a\nfortune. But the story did not tell the\nmost important feature that had led to\nthe union\u2014a young girl seeing an act.\nof cool bravery on the part of a young\nman.\nThe wedding of Barton Keith and\nAlice Forbes was not celebrated with\nthat splendor usual to nuptials in the\nfashionable world. It was said that\nthis was In deference to the wishes of\nthe groom, who bore the reputation\nof being an extremely modest man\nHe devoted himself to business, his\nonly recreation being driving four-in\nhands, and this was supposed to be in\nmemory of experiences of former days\n\".Mother,\" said Mary Murphy one\nday. \"I have a plan.\"\n\"What is it. Mame?\"\n\"We can't break through the shell of\nthis Newport egg We must go else\nwhere\"\n\"Where shall we go?\"\n\"To London.\"\n\"Good gracious, daughter! If we\ncan't succeed here, how can we do so\namong the British nobility?\"\n\"Others who have failed here have\nsucceeded there. Leave it to me\nMoney, dear mother, is the power that\nopens iloors wherever money is need\nful These British nobles are getting\npoor Our people are getting rich.\nMany here have always been rich, and\nsome care nothing about becoming\nricher In Iingland commoners have\nbeen getting rich, while the nobles\nhave been getting poor* -Noblemen\nwould prefer to marry an American to\na commoner of their own country,\nthere being no titles here. I shall go\nto London, marry a title aud come back\nhere for just long enough to, snub\nthose who have snubbed us.\"\nTwo years later Mary Murphy re\nturned to Newport as the countess of\nMunkennon. Her advent was herald\ned, and when she arrived invitations\nwere piled on her table. Before look\ning for those she intended to accept\nshe picked out those from certain peo\nple who hsd sntih'.ied her as Miss Mnr\nphy ami sent immediate \"regrets.\"\nI\nfl.SO\nPER\nBOZ.\n^if^-S\u00ae?^\nIT'S A WELL BEATEN PATH\nTHAT LEADS TO THE\nSisseton Standard\na\nO O W N O I S O W I N I N\nSISSETOX WEEKLY STANDARD $1.50 A YEAR\nTHE BEST NEW bJ'APKH IN ROBERTS COUNTY\nSuccessful Farming\nDepends as nuii'h on the ti.-e of\nup-tn-flute.\nfarm machines as it does upon good judf\n111 tint- in planning farti, work. Goon judg\nment must Ue backed up with tools t'.i